	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Rice prices could rise on back of government supply fears</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports are warning of possible increased volatility on rice markets in response to supply fears and government export restrictions. World rice prices have recently fallen to their lowest level in 3 years ‘to a little over half [of the] record levels reached in 2008’. Dr Mohanty of the International Rice Research Institute has however argued that ‘panic among rice-growing countries as recently evidenced by the actions of Indonesia, Bangladesh, and Myanmar – if it spreads to other countries – could easily rattle this market.’ ‘While the actions of three countries were, on their own, unlikely to make a big market impact’, he maintained that ‘this definitely serves as a warning bell considering what happened in 2008.’</p><p>Press reports also note that ‘concerns over rice supplies could be heightened in the coming season if drought persists in China’. China is the biggest rice-growing country in the world and reduced sowings could impact strongly on global markets. US rice farmers meanwhile are ‘expected to cut sowings by 20% to 1.15m hectares this year, in the rush to exploit soaring corn, cotton and soybean values.’ According to Dr Mohanty, ‘a combination of lower rice prices and higher input prices may force farmers to scale back rice production by planting less area and/or applying less fertilizer.’</p><p>In Southern Africa, with imports of 650,000 tonnes a year, Mozambique is looking to expand rice production by 20%. However this will require an expansion of land allocations to existing projects.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Trade moves ring “warning bell” over rice prices’, 12 April 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/trade-moves-ring-warning-bell-over-rice-prices--3037.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/trade-moves-ring-warning-bell-over-rice-pr...</a><br />
<i>Allafrica.com</i>, ‘Matutuine project could cut rice imports by 20%’, 13 April 2011<br />
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201104140235.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201104140235.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Concerted efforts are under way to promote rice production in Africa. In a number of regions this has enjoyed considerable success at the level of basic rice production. However, quality-related issues, linked to processing, storage, packaging and distribution of locally produced rice, are increasingly generating a continued consumer preference among urban consumers for imported rice.</p><p>Against this background, any reversal of the declines in international rice prices could offer renewed opportunities for investment in improving the quality of locally produced rice, as delivered to urban consumers. Government assistance in ‘pump priming’ investment in quality improvements may prove necessary in a number of countries, most notably in the West Africa region.</p>
		</div>
		
